Categorical Distributions:

Assembly: Balanced, with each assembly ( Bolgatanga, Tamale, … ) having 128 observations (16.67% each).

Revenue Item: Balanced, with each item ( Fees, Licenses., …, ) having 96 observations (12.5% each).

Type: Balanced, with Budget and Actuals each having 384 observations (50% each).

Revenue by Assembly:

Tamale has the highest mean revenue (419,028 GHS, median = 351,095 GHS) and maximum value (2,435,500 GHS), indicating strong performance, likely due to its urban status.

East Mamprusi and West Gonja have the lowest mean revenues (31,141 GHS and 69,571 GHS, respectively), suggesting lower revenue generation.

Somr of the standard deviations are large ( Tamale SD = 417,810 GHS, … ), reflecting possible outliers and skewness.

Revenue by Revenue Item:

Licenses has the highest mean (412,931 GHS, median = 273,633 GHS) and contributes 33.93% to total revenue, making it the largest revenue source.

Fees (mean = 268,034 GHS, 22.26% contribution) and Property Rates (mean = 166,148 GHS, 13.80%) are also significant.

Fines, Investment, and Other Rates have low means (42,983, 26,064, and 24,557 GHS) and contributions (<3% each), indicating minor roles.

High Variability: Licenses and Property Rates have high SDs (420,438 and 235,007 GHS), reflecting diverse revenue amounts.

Revenue by Type (Budget vs. Actuals):

Budget has a higher mean (177,580 GHS) and median (66,500 GHS) than Actuals (mean = 151,456 GHS, median = 58,007 GHS), suggesting consistent over-budgeting.

The box plot shows Budget values slightly higher if you would say than Actuals, with outliers in both (max Budget = 2,435,500 GHS, max Actuals = 2,107,371 GHS).

Revenue Trends by Year:

Upward Trend: Mean revenue increases from 130,630 GHS (2017) to 254,120 GHS (2024), a ~94% rise, with the largest jump in 2023–2024.

Median Trend: Median revenue rises from 46,006 GHS (2017) to 75,000 GHS (2024), indicating broader growth.

Variability: SD increases over time (156,073 GHS in 2017 to 427,929 GHS in 2024), reflecting growing disparities or outliers.

Patterns and Insights:

Dominant Assemblies: Tamale and Wa drive high revenue, while East Mamprusi and West Gonja lag, suggesting regional disparities.

Key Revenue Items: Licenses and Fees are primary revenue drivers, while Fines and Investment are consistently low.

Budget vs. Actuals Gap: Budgets overestimate Actuals (e.g., mean gap ~26,124 GHS), with gaps potentially widening in later years (2023–2024).

Outliers: High values ( 2,435,500 GHS in Licenses) skew means, but medians provide a better view of typical revenue.

Visualization: Histogram confirms right-skewness; box plot highlights Budget vs. Actuals slight differences and outliers.

Trends and Patterns Depicted

Overall Revenue Trend (2017–2024):

Line Plot by Assembly : Shows mean value over year for Budget and Actuals across each assembly. The upward trend in mean revenue (from 130,630 GHS in 2017 to 254,120 GHS in 2024, ~94% increase) , with Budget consistently higher than Actuals.

Pattern: Tamale shows the steepest growth (mean = 419,028 GHS), while East Mamprusi and West Gonja (means = 31,141 and 69,571 GHS) show flatter trends. Budget vs. Actuals gaps persist across years.

Revenue Distribution by Assembly and Type:

Box Plot by Assembly and Type: Highlights variability in value. Tamale has the highest median (351,095 GHS) and (up to 2,435,500 GHS), while East Mamprusi and West Gonja have lower medians (18,750 and ~30,018 GHS). Budget medians (66,500 GHS) exceed Actuals (58,007 GHS), confirming over-budgeting.

Pattern: High variability ( Tamale SD = 417,810 GHS) and outliers in urban assemblies (Tamale, Wa) contrast with lower, more stable revenues in rural ones (East Mamprusi, West Gonja).

Revenue Trends by Revenue Item:

Faceted Line Plot by Revenue Item: Shows mean value trends for each revenue_item. Licenses (mean = 412,931 GHS, 33.93% contribution) and Fees (mean = 268,034 GHS, 22.26%) show strong growth, while Fines (mean = 42,983 GHS) and Investment (mean = 26,064 GHS) remain low.

Pattern: Licenses and Fees drive revenue growth, while Fines and Other Rates contribute minimally (<3% each).

Distribution of Revenue by Assembly:

Faceted Histogram/Density Plot: Confirms right-skewed value (skewness = 3.31, kurtosis = 21.16) across assemblies. Tamale and Wa show wider distributions with high-value tails, while East Mamprusi and West Gonja are tightly clustered around lower values.

Pattern: Urban assemblies (Tamale, Wa) have more diverse revenue streams, while rural ones are constrained.

Overall Revenue Trend (2017–2024):

Line Plot by Year and Type: Mean revenue grows from 130,630 GHS (2017) to 254,120 GHS (2024), a ~94% increase. Budget (mean = 177,580 GHS) consistently exceeds Actuals (mean = 151,456 GHS), with gaps visible in the plot.

Time-Series: Decomposition (yearly data, frequency = 1) confirms an upward trend without seasonality, aligning with the ~94% growth.

Assembly-Specific Trends:

Line Plot by Assembly and Type: Tamale (mean = 419,028 GHS) shows the strongest growth, while East Mamprusi (mean = 31,141 GHS) and West Gonja (mean = 69,571 GHS) remain flat or low. Budget vs. Actuals gaps vary, with larger gaps in high-revenue assemblies liek Tamale.

Revenue Composition by Assembly: Stacked bar plot shows Tamale’s revenue is dominated by Licenses (33.93% total contribution) and Fees (22.26%), while East Mamprusi relies on smaller items like Fines, Investment and others .

Revenue Item Trends:

Faceted Line Plot by Revenue Item: Licenses, Fees, and Property Rates (top 3 items, contributing 33.93%, 22.26%, and 13.80%) show significant growth, especially post-2020. Fines and Investment (means = 42,983 and 26,064 GHS) are flat, contributing <3% each.

Top 3 Items Plot: Licenses, Fees, and Property Rates drive revenue, with Budget trends slightly above Actuals, indicating maybe over-forecasting likely I think.

Revenue Contribution by Year: Stacked bar plot confirms Licenses and Fees dominate annually, with increasing contributions in 2023–2024.

Budget vs. Actuals Gap: Annual Budget vs. Actuals Bar Plot: Total Budget revenue exceeds Actuals each year, with gaps widening in later years (e.g., 2024). For example, Bolgatanga’s 2024 Budget (2,620,000 GHS) vs. Actuals (2,023,753 GHS) shows a 22.8% shortfall.

Variance Heatmap: Actuals are consistently below Budget (negative variance_pct, -11.3% to -72.4% for Bolgatanga and East Mamprusi). East Mamprusi has the largest shortfalls ( -72.4% in 2018), low budget accuracy.

Variance Violin/Box Plot: Most assemblies show negative variance (Actuals < Budget), with Tamale having the widest distribution, while East Mamprusi is tightly clustered around large negative values.

Revenue Distribution and Variability: Faceted Bar Plot by Assembly and Revenue Item: Licenses and Fees have high mean values in Tamale and Wa, while Fines and Investment are low across all assemblies. Budget values are higher than Actuals for most items.

Key Insights:

Growth: Revenue growth is driven by Licenses and Fees, especially in Tamale, with a sharp increase in 2023–2024.

Budget Accuracy: Persistent over-budgeting (negative variance) is most severe in East Mamprusi and Bolgatanga, requiring forecasting improvements.

Regional Disparities: Urban assemblies (Tamale, Wa) have higher, more variable revenues; rural ones (East Mamprusi, West Gonja) are lower and stable.

Minor Items: Fines and Investment contribute little, suggesting policy focus on these areas.

Assembly-Specific Differences:

ANOVA: Significant differences across assemblies (p < 0.001 for both Budget and Actuals). Tamale’s high mean (419,028 GHS) contrasts with East Mamprusi (31,141 GHS) and West Gonja (69,571 GHS).

Key Insights from the analysis

Significant Revenue Growth:

Total revenue grew ~94% from 130,630 GHS (2017) to 254,120 GHS (2024), with Actuals increasing by ~17,898 GHS per year (p = 0.000392, linear regression). Growth accelerated in 2023–2024, driven by urban assemblies and key revenue items.

Dominant Revenue Sources:

Licenses (33.93% contribution, mean = 412,931 GHS), Fees (22.26%, mean = 268,034 GHS), and Property Rates (13.80%, mean = 166,148 GHS) account for ~70% of revenue, showing strong growth. Fines (2.96%) and Investment (1.31%) contribute minimally, suggesting policy focus on these areas.

Assembly Disparities:

Tamale leads with the highest mean revenue (419,028 GHS, +199,240 GHS vs. Bolgatanga, p < 0.001), driven by Licenses and Fees. East Mamprusi (mean = 31,141 GHS, -163,647 GHS, p < 0.001) and West Gonja (mean = 69,571 GHS, -130,370 GHS, p < 0.001) lag significantly. ANOVA confirms assembly differences (p < 0.001).

Persistent Budget Overestimation: Budgets (mean = 177,580 GHS) consistently exceed Actuals (mean = 151,456 GHS), with variance percentages ranging from -11.3% to -72.4% ( East Mamprusi, -72.4% in 2018). The Wilcoxon test (p = 0.0786) suggests a near-significant gap. Budget accuracy is poorest in East Mamprusi.

  • Conclusion

The analysis reveals robust revenue growth in Ghana’s assemblies (2017–2024), led by Licenses and Fees in Tamale, but highlights significant challenges: stark assembly disparities, persistent over-budgeting (especially in East Mamprusi), and underperforming revenue items (Fines, Investment). Policymakers should focus on improving budget accuracy, boosting minor revenue streams, and addressing regional inequalities.
